04327nam a22005415i 9780226427034DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016018415  a97802264270347 a10.7208/97802264270342doi  a(DE-B1597)550024  a(OCoLC)1229161755  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aSB409.48b.E64 2016 4aSB409.48b.E64 2016 7aNAT0000002bisacsh04a584.42221 aEndersby, Jim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOrchid :bA Cultural History /cJim Endersby. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b15 color plates, 45 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Imagining Orchids -- t1. Censored Origins -- t2. Red Book, Black Flower -- t3. The Name of the Orchid -- t4. Orchidmania -- t5. Orchis Bank -- t6. The Scramble for Orchids -- t7. Savage Orchids -- t8. Sexy Orchids -- t9. Manly Orchids -- t10. Deceptive Orchids -- t11. Endangered Orchids -- tConclusion: An Orchid’s-Eye View? -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt once delicate, exotic, and elegant, orchids are beloved for their singular, instantly recognizable beauty. Found in nearly every climate, the many species of orchid have carried symbolic weight in countless cultures over time. The ancient Greeks associated them with fertility and thought that parents who ingested orchid root tubers could control the sex of their child. During the Victorian era, orchids became deeply associated with romance and seduction. And in twentieth-century hard-boiled detective stories, they transformed into symbols of decadence, secrecy, and cunning. What is it about the orchid that has enthralled the imagination for so many centuries? And why do they still provoke so much wonder? Following the stories of orchids throughout history, Jim Endersby divides our attraction to them into four key themes: science, empire, sex, and death. When it comes to empire, for instance, orchids are a prime example of the exotic riches sought by Europeans as they shaped their plans for colonization. He also reveals how Charles Darwin’s theory of evolution became intimately entangled with the story of the orchid as he investigated their methods of cross-pollination. As he shows, orchids—perhaps because of their extraordinarily diverse colors, shapes, and sizes—have also bloomed repeatedly in films, novels, plays, and poems, from Shakespeare to science fiction, from thrillers to elaborate modernist novels. Featuring many gorgeous illustrations from the collection of the Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, Orchid: A Cultural History tells, for the first time, the extraordinary story of orchids and our prolific interest in them. It is an enchanting tale not only for gardeners and plant collectors, but anyone curious about the flower’s obsessive hold on the imagination in history, cinema, literature, and more.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aOrchids in literaturexHistory. 0aOrchids in literature. 0aOrchidsxHistory. 0aOrchids. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226427034423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226427034.jpg  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles